<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Facility Availability:&lt;/strong&gt; Coordinate with other facility projects&lt;/li&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Budget Cycles:&lt;/strong&gt; Align with fiscal year and budget approval processes&lt;/li&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Recruiting Calendar:&lt;/strong&gt; Complete before official visit season&lt;/li&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;/ul&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;We recommend starting the planning process 3-4 months before your target completion date to ensure adequate time for design, fabrication, and installation.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;h2 id="maintenance"&gt;Maintenance &amp; Longevity Planning&lt;/h2&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;h3&gt;Maintenance: It's Easier Than You Think&lt;/h3&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;One of the questions we get all the time: "How much maintenance do these lockers need?"&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;The answer? Not much. Seriously.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;Weekly, your facilities staff should wipe down the surfaces with a mild cleaner and check for any obvious damage. That's it. Takes maybe 15 minutes for a whole locker room.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;Monthly, do a deeper clean and check the hardware and locks. Make sure ventilation systems are working. Again, not a huge time commitment.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;Annually, do a full inspection, lubricate hardware if needed, and touch up any finish issues. Most programs don't even need the touch-ups for the first 5-7 years.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;Compare that to metal lockers, where you're constantly dealing with rust spots, dents, and hardware that's corroding. We had one facilities manager tell us that switching to wood lockers cut his maintenance time in half. The wood just holds up better, especially in humid locker room environments.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;And here's the best part: our lifetime guarantee covers manufacturing defects. So if something's wrong with how we built it, we fix it. No questions asked. With proper maintenance (which, again, is minimal), these lockers last 15-20+ years. We've got installations from the 1990s that are still going strong.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;h3&gt;Modular Repair System&lt;/h3&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;One of the key advantages of custom wood lockers is the modular repair system. Individual components can be replaced without replacing entire lockers:&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;ul&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Damaged Door:&lt;/strong&gt; Replace just the door (\$50-\$150)&lt;/li&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Broken Shelf:&lt;/strong&gt; Replace just the shelf (\$30-\$75)&lt;/li&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Worn Hardware:&lt;/strong&gt; Replace hardware components (\$20-\$50)&lt;/li&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;/ul&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;This modular approach extends locker lifespan significantly and reduces long-term costs compared to metal lockers that require full replacement.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;h2 id="common-mistakes"&gt;Common Mistakes College Programs Make&lt;/h2&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;h3&gt;Five Mistakes We See Programs Make (And How to Avoid Them)&lt;/h3&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mistake #1: Only Looking at the Per-Locker Price&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;This one drives us crazy. Programs will call and say, "I've got \$50,000 and I need 100 lockers, so I can afford \$500 per locker, right?"&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;Wrong. That \$500 per locker doesn't include installation (\$50-\$150 per locker), shipping (\$20-\$50 per locker), or site prep (\$5,000-\$20,000). So your \$50,000 budget actually gets you maybe 70-80 lockers when you factor in everything else.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;Always plan for the full project cost, not just the locker cost. Our consultations include complete cost breakdowns so you know exactly what you're getting into.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mistake #2: Designing for One Sport, Forgetting About Others&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;We worked with a program that designed their lockers specifically for football. Perfect for shoulder pads, helmets, all that bulky equipment. Then basketball season rolled around, and the lockers were way too big. Players were complaining about wasted space, and the program realized they'd designed themselves into a corner.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;The solution? Flexible configurations. Adjustable shelving, removable dividers, lockers that can adapt as sports change. Don't lock yourself into one configuration—build in flexibility from the start.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mistake #3: Waiting Until the Last Minute to Think About Compliance&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;We had a program call us in a panic once. They'd already ordered lockers from another manufacturer, and halfway through installation, someone asked about ADA compliance. Turns out they hadn't planned for it at all, and they had to rip everything out and start over.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;Don't be that program. Address compliance requirements during the design phase, not after you've already ordered. It'll save you time, money, and a lot of headaches.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mistake #4: Going Cheap Now, Paying More Later&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;We get it. Budgets are tight. But here's what happens when you go with the cheapest option: metal lockers that cost \$300 per locker instead of wood lockers at \$449.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;Three years later, you're dealing with rust spots. Five years later, dents everywhere. Ten years later, you're replacing them entirely because they're falling apart. Meanwhile, the wood lockers are still going strong.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;Look at total cost of ownership, not just upfront price. Those \$300 metal lockers that need replacing after 10 years? Over 15 years, they actually cost more than \$449 wood lockers that last 20 years.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mistake #5: Starting Too Late&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;We got a call in July once. "We need 100 lockers installed by August 15th for fall camp."&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&lt;p&gt;Sorry, not happening. Not if you want it done right. We need 10-16 weeks from order to completion, and that's if everything goes perfectly. Start planning 3-4 months before you need it done. Trust us on this one.&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
